\begin{center}
{
\Large
The Glob and Regular Expressions
}
\vspace{0.1in}
\end{center}

\begin{note}
In this notes packet, you will learn two new \emph{query programming languages}: the Glob and Regular Expressions (regex).
These languages are similar to CSS Selectors in that:
(1) they are used to "find" information inside another filetype;
(2) they are commonly used from within other languages.
\end{note}

\section{Glob}

\begin{note}
The glob is used for creating a "list" of files that match a particular pattern.
You are responsible for the following syntax:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ll}
\toprule
Pattern & Matches \\
\midrule
\texttt{*} & any string (including empty) \\
\texttt{?} & exactly one character \\
\texttt{[abc]} & one character in the set \\
\texttt{[\textasciicircum abc]} & one character not in the set \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\end{note}

\subsection{With the Shell}

\begin{note}
The glob is always applied to any arguments that are passed into a program.
\end{note}

\begin{note}
Anytime we write code that uses the glob, we say we are \emph{globbing}.
\end{note}

